\section{Introduction}

With the rapid development of IIoT technology, massive volumes of sensor data are
continuously generated across smart manufacturing, industrial
automation, and critical infrastructure environments~\cite{ref1,ref2}.
To reduce storage and operational costs, organizations commonly
outsource these data to cloud platforms. However, cloud servers
are generally considered semi-honest entities that may attempt
to infer sensitive operational information from outsourced
data~\cite{ref3,ref4}. Consequently, IIoT data must be encrypted
before outsourcing. Unfortunately, conventional encryption
significantly complicates efficient retrieval and analytics over
encrypted numerical sensor data.

Searchable encryption (SE) enables users to retrieve encrypted
data without revealing plaintext information to the cloud
server~\cite{ref3,ref4}. Existing searchable encryption and
attribute-based searchable encryption (ABSE)
schemes~\cite{ref5,ref8,ref11} mainly focus on keyword
retrieval and are not well suited for IIoT environments,
where queries often involve numerical conditions and
real-time analytics. Recent studies have improved verifiable
search~\cite{ref7,ref10,ref43,ref44,ref45},
search-pattern privacy~\cite{ref21}, dynamic access control
and update privacy~\cite{ref23,ref25}, and privacy-preserving
trapdoor generation~\cite{ref23}. However, most remain
keyword-oriented and do not efficiently support conjunctive
numerical range queries with encrypted aggregation.

In practical IIoT environments, operators frequently issue
conjunctive multi-range queries over multiple sensor
attributes while simultaneously performing statistical
analysis on the matched records. For example, a factory
operator may search for records satisfying

\[
\begin{aligned}
\mathrm{Temperature} &\in [60^\circ\mathrm{C},80^\circ\mathrm{C}] \\
\land\;\mathrm{Vibration} &\in [10,20] \\
\land\;\mathrm{Pressure} &\in [40,55].
\end{aligned}
\]

while computing the sum, count, or average of the matched
sensor readings. Supporting such \emph{conjunctive range
search} and \emph{secure aggregation} directly over encrypted
IIoT data remains challenging.

First, existing range-query schemes primarily focus on secure
retrieval. Approaches in~\cite{ref19,ref25,ref30} improve
encrypted search, while learned-index schemes~\cite{ref43},
Volume-Hiding SSE~\cite{ref36}, Revocable
DSSE~\cite{ref37}, Scheme~\cite{ref38}, and
Trinity~\cite{ref39} enhance query efficiency, privacy, and
scalability. ABSE-Range~\cite{ref40} and lattice-based
searchable encryption~\cite{ref41} further introduce
attribute-based and post-quantum range-query support.
Nevertheless, these schemes do not jointly support
conjunctive range search and encrypted aggregation.

Second, searchable encryption and encrypted analytics are
typically treated as separate components. Recent
schemes~\cite{ref7,ref12,ref21,ref23,ref25,ref43,ref44,ref45}
combine searchable encryption with homomorphic computation,
query privacy, access control, and verifiable search.
However, aggregation is usually performed outside the search
structure, introducing additional computation and
communication overhead.

Third, existing verifiable searchable encryption schemes
mainly focus on retrieval correctness and rarely verify both
conjunctive range search and aggregation results. A
malicious cloud may omit valid records, forge results,
manipulate aggregates, or replay stale query states.
Although blockchain-assisted approaches exist, most rely on
simple timestamping or Merkle-root anchoring and do not
authenticate searchable indexes, aggregation metadata, and
query results in a unified manner. Consequently, ensuring
search correctness, aggregation integrity, freshness, and
rollback resistance remains an open challenge for large-scale
outsourced IIoT environments.

To address these limitations, we propose
\emph{Blockchain-based Verifiable Conjunctive Range Search
and Aggregation (BVCRSA)}, a blockchain-anchored framework
for secure and verifiable conjunctive multi-range queries
over encrypted IIoT data. BVCRSA combines authenticated
hierarchical range-cover structures, protected bitmap
filtering, and cross-dimensional bitmap intersection to
enable efficient canonical-node discovery and conjunctive
range evaluation. It further integrates ABSE with Threshold
EC-ElGamal homomorphic encryption to provide fine-grained
access control and direct aggregation over matched encrypted
records. An epoch-bound blockchain verification mechanism
based on authenticated Merkle proofs and compact aggregation
commitments ensures correctness, integrity, freshness, and
rollback resistance without relying on zero-knowledge proofs
or trusted hardware. The main contributions of this paper are summarized as
follows:

\begin{itemize}

\item We propose \textbf{BVCRSA}, a unified framework for
verifiable conjunctive range search and encrypted analytics
over outsourced IIoT data. Unlike existing schemes that
treat searchable encryption, aggregation, and verification
independently, BVCRSA jointly realizes secure
multi-dimensional range search, privacy-preserving
aggregation, fine-grained access control, and authenticated
query-state verification within a single architecture.

\item We design an \textbf{authenticated hierarchical
range-cover indexing mechanism} that transforms
multi-dimensional range queries into compact canonical
interval representations. Combined with protected bitmap
filtering and cross-dimensional bitmap intersection, the
proposed mechanism enables logarithmic searchable-node
lookup and efficient conjunctive query evaluation over
encrypted numerical sensor data.

\item We develop a \textbf{bitmap-aware encrypted
aggregation mechanism} that tightly couples searchable
indexing with homomorphic aggregation, enabling direct
computation of sum, count, and average statistics over
query-matched encrypted IIoT records under fine-grained
authorization. The proposed design eliminates separate
aggregation processing while ensuring that no single entity
can decrypt the aggregation results.

\item We introduce a \textbf{Verifiable Query-State
Anchoring (VQSA)} mechanism that authenticates searchable
index states, bitmap commitments, and aggregation metadata
through compact blockchain-anchored commitments. By
combining blockchain finality with Merkle-based
verification, VQSA provides authenticated query-state
integrity, authenticated completeness, freshness, rollback
resistance, and cryptographic binding between aggregation
ciphertexts and the verified matched record set, without
requiring zero-knowledge proofs, cryptographic
accumulators, or trusted hardware.

\end{itemize}

The rest of this paper is organized as follows.
Section~II reviews related work.
Section~III presents the proposed BVCRSA framework.
Section~IV provides formal security analysis.
Section~V evaluates the performance of the proposed scheme.
Finally, Section~VI concludes the paper.



