\subsection{Verifiable Searchable Encryption and Attribute-Based Search}

Verifiable searchable encryption (VSE) enables users to
validate the correctness and integrity of outsourced
encrypted search results, while attribute-based searchable
encryption (ABSE) provides fine-grained access control over
encrypted data. Early ABSE schemes~\cite{ref8} introduced
attribute-constrained search, and subsequent studies
extended the paradigm with hierarchical
search~\cite{ref9}, hidden access
policies~\cite{ref15}, multi-keyword
search~\cite{ref5,ref6,ref11},
blockchain-assisted auditability~\cite{ref17,ref18},
wildcard and revocable
search~\cite{ref16,ref20}, and resistance to
keyword-guessing and leakage
attacks~\cite{ref31,ref32,ref33}. These schemes
significantly improve search privacy and authorization but
remain primarily designed for keyword retrieval rather than
numerical range queries.

Recent VSE schemes~\cite{ref7,ref10,ref43,ref44,ref45}
further strengthen authenticated query verification,
authorization-aware delegation, provenance validation, and
blockchain-assisted integrity protection. For example,
LV-PQ-ABSE~\cite{ref45} combines post-quantum
attribute-based searchable encryption with provenance-aware
verification for IoT-enabled EHR systems. Nevertheless,
these schemes remain keyword-oriented and generally do not
support conjunctive multi-dimensional range search or
privacy-preserving aggregation. Dynamic searchable
encryption~\cite{ref23,ref25} further improves update
privacy, data deduplication, and conjunctive keyword search,
while search-pattern hiding and privacy-preserving trapdoor
generation~\cite{ref21,ref23} reduce query leakage.
However, efficient authenticated numerical analytics remain
largely unexplored.

\subsection{Privacy-Preserving Range Query}

Privacy-preserving range-query processing has been widely
studied for encrypted databases and IoT systems.
Order-preserving and order-revealing
encryption~\cite{ref29} support efficient ciphertext
comparison but inherently leak ordering information.
Existing encrypted range-query
schemes~\cite{ref19,ref25,ref30} improve secure retrieval
for numerical and spatial data but provide only limited
support for conjunctive multi-dimensional queries and do
not incorporate encrypted analytics. Learned-index
approaches~\cite{ref43} further improve retrieval
efficiency but primarily optimize indexing performance
rather than integrating access control, aggregation, or
authenticated verification.

Several studies focus on improving the scalability of
encrypted range search. Volume-Hiding
SSE~\cite{ref36} reduces information leakage during
retrieval, Revocable DSSE~\cite{ref37} supports dynamic
healthcare-oriented search, Scheme~\cite{ref38} enables
efficient multidimensional range queries, and
Trinity~\cite{ref39} introduces forward-secure
spatio-temporal search using SHVE and quotient filters.
Although these schemes improve search efficiency and query
expressiveness, they generally treat retrieval as an
independent task and do not provide integrated encrypted
aggregation or authenticated result verification.

Recent efforts have combined range queries with
attribute-based and post-quantum searchable encryption.
ABSE-Range~\cite{ref40} supports numerical range queries
under attribute-based authorization but incurs increasing
trapdoor complexity as the query range expands.
Lattice-based searchable
encryption~\cite{ref41} provides post-quantum security
under LWE assumptions but introduces substantially higher
computational overhead due to expensive lattice
operations, limiting practicality for resource-constrained
IIoT deployments.

\subsection{Searchable Encryption with Privacy-Preserving Aggregation}

Homomorphic encryption enables computations to be performed
directly over encrypted data and has recently been combined
with searchable encryption to support secure cloud
analytics. The verifiable searchable encryption
framework~\cite{ref7} integrates partial homomorphic
encryption, B$+$-Tree indexing, bitmap filtering, and
blockchain-assisted verification for Boolean search.
SEaaS~\cite{ref12} combines searchable encryption with
homomorphic computation for encrypted analytics, while
other studies~\cite{ref21,ref23,ref25} improve query
privacy, update privacy, and multi-user searchable
encryption.

Despite these advances, existing solutions generally
optimize one aspect of the problem---search efficiency,
encrypted analytics, or verifiable query
processing---without jointly addressing all requirements of
large-scale IIoT data analytics. In particular, encrypted
aggregation is typically performed independently of the
search process, introducing additional computation,
communication, and post-processing overhead. Furthermore,
authenticated verification mechanisms mainly focus on
retrieval correctness rather than simultaneously ensuring
search correctness, aggregation integrity, completeness,
freshness, and rollback resistance.

Table~\ref{tab:feature_comparison} summarizes the
functional capabilities of representative searchable
encryption schemes. Verifiable searchable encryption
schemes~\cite{ref7,ref44,ref45} provide authenticated
search and integrity validation, but
Refs.~\cite{ref7,ref44} do not support numerical range
queries, while Ref.~\cite{ref45} lacks encrypted
aggregation. Range-query
schemes~\cite{ref36,ref37,ref38,ref39,ref40,ref41}
improve retrieval efficiency and query expressiveness but
generally omit authenticated verification and integrated
encrypted aggregation. Conversely,
SEaaS~\cite{ref12} supports encrypted aggregation but does
not provide conjunctive range search, fine-grained
attribute-based access control, or verifiable query
processing.

In contrast, BVCRSA integrates authenticated hierarchical
range-cover indexing, conjunctive bitmap filtering,
attribute-based searchable encryption, Threshold
EC-ElGamal homomorphic aggregation, and blockchain-anchored
query-state verification within a unified framework. This
integration enables efficient conjunctive multi-range
search together with fine-grained access control,
privacy-preserving aggregation, authenticated query-state
integrity, completeness, freshness, and rollback
resistance, thereby addressing the limitations of existing
searchable encryption schemes for large-scale IIoT
analytics.


\section{Our Proposed Scheme}
\subsection{System Model}
\label{subsec:system_model}

The proposed BVCRSA architecture consists of seven entities,
as illustrated in Fig.~\ref{fig:system_model}. The system
supports privacy-preserving conjunctive range search,
encrypted aggregation, threshold-secure aggregate
decryption, and blockchain-anchored result verification over
outsourced IIoT data. Unlike conventional designs that
require sensor data to be decrypted at an intermediate edge
node, BVCRSA performs encryption directly at the sensor. Each
sensor locally derives the canonical-node identifiers
required for indexing and transmits them as authenticated
metadata. The Edge Gateway constructs the authenticated
searchable index from this metadata without decrypting the
sensor record or aggregation ciphertext.

\begin{enumerate}

\item \textbf{IIoT Sensor Nodes.}
Resource-constrained devices continuously collect industrial
measurements and generate sensor records. Before
outsourcing, each sensor derives authenticated indexing
metadata, encrypts the complete record using AES-GCM,
encrypts the numerical value using Threshold EC-ElGamal for
privacy-preserving aggregation, and generates authentication
tags to ensure data integrity and freshness.

\item \textbf{Edge Gateway.}
The Edge Gateway is an honest-but-curious entity
responsible for verifying sensor authenticity,
constructing the authenticated range-cover index,
generating protected bitmap structures, maintaining
aggregation metadata, and producing blockchain-bound
authenticated commitments. It is trusted to correctly
generate these authenticated states but may attempt to
infer information from encrypted records and indexing
metadata. The gateway does not possess any threshold
decryption share or attribute secret key and therefore
cannot decrypt encrypted sensor records or aggregation
ciphertexts.


\item \textbf{Cloud Server.}
The Cloud Server faithfully executes storage, search, and
aggregation protocols but is curious about the outsourced
data and queries. In addition, the framework considers
active attacks in which a compromised or malicious cloud
attempts to omit, modify, replay, or fabricate query
results. Such attacks are detected through blockchain-based
query-state verification, authenticated batch commitments,
and Merkle-proof validation.

\item \textbf{Blockchain Network.}
The blockchain acts as an immutable commitment layer that
stores authenticated query-state commitments generated by
the Edge Gateway. It provides integrity protection,
freshness validation, and rollback resistance without
storing encrypted sensor records or searchable indexes
on-chain.

\item \textbf{Data User.}
Authorized users generate query trapdoors using their
attribute secret keys, submit encrypted conjunctive range
queries to the cloud, verify the returned authenticated
query response against the blockchain commitments, and
request threshold decryption of the authenticated aggregate
ciphertexts. Users do not possess any threshold decryption
share and therefore cannot decrypt individual aggregation
ciphertexts independently.

\item \textbf{Threshold Decryption Authorities (TDAs).}
The TDAs are independent and non-colluding entities that
collectively perform threshold EC-ElGamal decryption of
authenticated aggregate ciphertexts. Each TDA stores a
single secret decryption share and generates a partial
decryption only after the corresponding authenticated query
response has been successfully verified. Aggregate
ciphertexts are recovered only through the cooperation of
at least \(t\) out of \(n\) TDAs, while fewer than \(t\)
shares reveal no information about the underlying
decryption key.

\item \textbf{Trusted Authority (TA).}
The TA is assumed to be fully trusted during system
initialization and serves as the root of trust for the
proposed framework. It generates the global public
parameters, issues attribute-based secret keys,
initializes the Threshold EC-ElGamal cryptosystem,
constructs and distributes threshold decryption shares to
the TDAs, provisions cryptographic credentials to sensors,
users, and the Edge Gateway, and publishes the authenticated
public parameters required for encryption, authentication,
aggregation, threshold decryption, and verification. After
system setup, the TA does not participate in searchable
query processing, encrypted aggregation, or result
verification.
\end{enumerate}

