\subsection{Threat Model}

We consider probabilistic polynomial-time (PPT)
adversaries that attempt to infer sensor values, recover
query semantics, violate access policies, manipulate
aggregation results, or tamper with authenticated query
states.

\subsubsection{Honest-but-Curious Edge Gateway}

The Edge Gateway faithfully executes sensor
authentication, authenticated index construction,
aggregation-metadata generation, and blockchain commitment
generation, but may attempt to infer information from
encrypted records and authenticated indexing metadata. In
particular, it may observe the searchable dimensions and
canonical-node memberships contained in \(Meta_i\), but
does not learn the exact numerical sensor values.
Moreover, it possesses neither the ABSE master secret,
attribute secret keys, nor any threshold decryption share,
and therefore cannot decrypt sensor records or aggregation
ciphertexts. The authenticated query state generated by the
Edge Gateway is subsequently anchored on the blockchain,
allowing any unauthorized modification to be detected
during query-state verification.
\subsubsection{Honest-but-Curious Cloud Server}

The cloud is assumed to be honest-but-curious during
normal protocol execution, faithfully performing
searchable query processing, bitmap filtering, and
homomorphic aggregation while attempting to infer
information from encrypted records, trapdoors, protected
bitmaps, and the leakage specified by
\(\mathcal{L}_{BVCRSA}\). Separately, in the security
analysis, we consider protocol deviations in which the
cloud attempts to omit, modify, replay, or fabricate query
responses. These malicious behaviors are detected through
blockchain-anchored query states, authenticated batch
commitments, and Merkle-proof verification. Furthermore,
the cloud cannot decrypt encrypted data, generate
unauthorized trapdoors, or forge authenticated query
states without detection.
\subsubsection{Unauthorized Users and Threshold Decryption Authorities}

Unauthorized users may attempt to generate valid
trapdoors, bypass access policies, or collude with the
cloud. Aggregate ciphertexts are protected using
Threshold EC-ElGamal, where each Threshold Decryption
Authority (TDA) stores only one secret decryption share.
We assume fewer than \(t\) out of \(n\) TDAs are
compromised. Consequently, no coalition of the cloud,
users, and fewer than \(t\) TDAs can decrypt individual
ciphertexts or recover the aggregation private key.

\subsubsection{Blockchain and Network Attacks}

Adversaries may attempt rollback, replay, omission,
message tampering, or aggregation-result forgery.
Blockchain-anchored authenticated commitments, Merkle
proofs, authenticated batch commitments, AES-GCM, and
randomized ABSE trapdoors prevent such attacks while
providing integrity, freshness, and authenticated query
verification.

\subsubsection{Assumptions}

The Trusted Authority is fully trusted for system
initialization and credential distribution. The underlying
cryptographic primitives, Threshold EC-ElGamal scheme, and
blockchain consensus protocol are assumed to be secure.
Physical attacks, denial-of-service attacks, side-channel
attacks, and collusion among at least \(t\) TDAs are
outside the scope of this work.

