\subsubsection*{\textbf{Phase 1 --- System Setup}}

The Trusted Authority (TA) initializes the global
cryptographic parameters and securely distributes the
required credentials. Let \(\lambda\) denote the security
parameter. The TA defines the attribute universe
\(\mathcal U\) and the searchable numerical dimensions
\(\mathcal D=\{D_1,D_2,\ldots,D_d\}\).

\paragraph*{Step 1: ABSE and Selector-Key Initialization}

The TA initializes the attribute-based searchable
encryption (ABSE) scheme

\begin{equation}
(PP,MSK)
\leftarrow
\textsf{ABSE.Setup}(1^\lambda),
\end{equation}

where \(PP\) contains the BN254 (BN128) bilinear pairing
parameters
\((p,\mathbb G_1,\mathbb G_T,e,g)\)
and associated hash functions, while \(MSK\) denotes the
ABSE master secret key.

For each authorized user with attribute set
\(\mathcal A\subseteq\mathcal U\), the TA generates

\begin{equation}
SK_{\mathcal A}
\leftarrow
\textsf{ABSE.KeyGen}
(MSK,\mathcal A).
\end{equation}

The TA also generates a long-term bitmap-selector secret

\begin{equation}
K_s
\xleftarrow{\$}
\{0,1\}^{\lambda},
\end{equation}

which is securely distributed only to authorized users and
never revealed to the Edge Gateway or the cloud. For each
query epoch \(e_q\), the user derives the query-specific
selector key

\begin{equation}
K_s'
=
H
\bigl(
K_s
\parallel
e_q
\bigr),
\end{equation}

which is used only during trapdoor generation and bitmap
selector construction for the current query epoch.

\paragraph*{Step 2: Threshold Homomorphic Encryption Initialization}

The TA initializes lifted Threshold EC-ElGamal over the
NIST P-256 elliptic curve. Let
\((\mathbb G,G,p)\)
denote the prime-order cyclic group generated by
\(G\). The TA samples

\[
x
\xleftarrow{\$}
\mathbb Z_p^*,
\]

computes the public key

\[
pk_{AHE}
=
P
=
xG,
\]

and constructs a random polynomial

\[
f(z)
=
x
+
a_1z
+\cdots+
a_{t-1}z^{t-1},
\]

where
\(a_i\xleftarrow{\$}\mathbb Z_p^*\).

The TA distributes Shamir secret shares

\[
sk_\ell
=
f(\ell),
\qquad
\ell=1,\ldots,n,
\]

to \(n\) Threshold Decryption Authorities (TDAs), such
that any subset of at least \(t\) TDAs can jointly decrypt
an aggregate ciphertext, whereas fewer than \(t\) shares
reveal no information about \(x\).

A plaintext value
\(v\in\mathbb Z\)
is encrypted as

\begin{equation}
CT_v
=
(C_1,C_2)
=
(rG,\,
vG+rP),
\qquad
r
\xleftarrow{\$}
\mathbb Z_p^*,
\end{equation}

which satisfies the additive homomorphic property

\[
\textsf{Enc}(v_1)
+
\textsf{Enc}(v_2)
=
\textsf{Enc}(v_1+v_2).
\]

Only a threshold of authenticated TDAs can recover the
final aggregation result; no individual entity possesses
the complete decryption key.

\paragraph*{Step 3: Cryptographic Primitive Initialization}

The TA initializes the following cryptographic primitives:

\begin{align}
F(\cdot,\cdot)
&:
\{0,1\}^{\lambda}
\times
\{0,1\}^{*}
\rightarrow
\{0,1\}^{256},
\\
H_g
&:
\{0,1\}^{*}
\rightarrow
\mathbb G_1,
\\
H
&:
\{0,1\}^{*}
\rightarrow
\{0,1\}^{256},
\\
\textsf{KDF}
&:
\{0,1\}^{\lambda}
\times
\{0,1\}^{*}
\rightarrow
\{0,1\}^{256},
\\
\mathsf{DS}
&=
(
\mathsf{KeyGen},
\mathsf{Sign},
\mathsf{Verify}
).
\end{align}

Here,
\(F\) is instantiated using HMAC-SHA-256,
\(H_g\) denotes a hash-to-group function over BN254,
\(H\) is SHA-256,
\(\textsf{KDF}\) is HKDF-SHA-256,
and
\(\mathsf{DS}\)
is instantiated using ECDSA over the secp256k1 elliptic
curve with SHA-256. The digital signature scheme is
assumed to be existentially unforgeable under adaptive
chosen-message attacks (EUF-CMA).

\paragraph*{Step 4: Sensor Provisioning}

For each sensor node \(i\), the TA securely provisions the
sensor and its corresponding Edge Gateway with

\begin{itemize}
\item a 256-bit AES-GCM key
\[
K_{AES}^{(i)}
=
\textsf{KDF}(K_{master},ID_i),
\]

\item an HMAC authentication key
\[
K_{HMAC}^{(i)}
=
\textsf{KDF}
(K_{master},
ID_i\parallel\texttt{"hmac"}),
\]

\item the public threshold homomorphic encryption key
\(pk_{AHE}\).
\end{itemize}

The sensor uses \(K_{AES}^{(i)}\) with a unique 96-bit
AES-GCM nonce for each record encryption and computes an
HMAC over the authenticated payload using
\(K_{HMAC}^{(i)}\). The corresponding Edge Gateway uses
\(K_{HMAC}^{(i)}\) to verify sensor authenticity and
freshness, and \(K_{AES}^{(i)}\) only to generate
ABSE-protected key envelopes for authorized users.
Neither entity possesses \(MSK\), \(K_{sel}\), any
threshold decryption share \(sk_\ell\), or any attribute
secret key.
\paragraph*{Step 5: Edge Gateway, User, and TDA Initialization}

The TA samples a secret bitmap-selector seed

\[
K_{sel}
\in
\{0,1\}^{\lambda},
\]

and generates the Edge Gateway digital-signature key pair

\begin{equation}
(pk_{DO},sk_{DO})
\leftarrow
\mathsf{DS.KeyGen}
(1^\lambda).
\end{equation}

The bitmap-selector seed \(K_{sel}\) is securely
distributed to the Edge Gateway and authorized users
through authenticated channels, whereas the private
signing key \(sk_{DO}\) is provisioned exclusively to the
Edge Gateway. The corresponding public verification key
\(pk_{DO}\) is published as part of the authenticated
public system parameters.

The threshold decryption shares

\[
sk_\ell,
\qquad
\ell=1,\ldots,n,
\]

are securely provisioned to the corresponding Threshold
Decryption Authorities. Neither \(K_{sel}\),
\(sk_{DO}\), nor any threshold decryption share is
disclosed to the cloud server, sensors, or authorized
users.

The Edge Gateway uses \(K_{sel}\) to generate epoch-bound
bitmap masks during authenticated index construction and
uses \(sk_{DO}\) to digitally sign authenticated query
states before blockchain anchoring. Authorized users
derive node-specific selectors from \(K_{sel}\) during
trapdoor generation. Aggregate ciphertexts are decrypted only after the
authenticated query response has been successfully verified
and at least \(t\) Threshold Decryption Authorities
cooperatively perform the threshold decryption protocol.

\paragraph*{Step 6: Blockchain Commitment Initialization}

The TA initializes the authenticated commitment for the
searchable index, aggregation metadata, and bitmap
commitments by computing

\begin{equation}
Acc_e
=
H
\Bigl(
Root_e^{idx}
\parallel
Root_e^{agg}
\parallel
Root_e^{bmp}
\Bigr),
\end{equation}

followed by the epoch commitment

\begin{equation}
Root_e
=
H
\Bigl(
Acc_e
\parallel
e
\Bigr).
\end{equation}

The genesis commitment \(Root_0\) is anchored on the
blockchain during system deployment and serves as the
initial authenticated system state.

Finally, the TA publishes the authenticated public system
parameters

\[
(PP,\,
pk_{AHE},\,
pk_{DO},\,
\{pk_\ell\}_{\ell=1}^{n}),
\]

where \(pk_{AHE}\) is the threshold EC-ElGamal public key,
\(pk_{DO}\) is the Edge Gateway signature-verification key,
and \(pk_\ell\) denotes the public verification key of the
\(\ell\)-th Threshold Decryption Authority.

The following credentials remain confidential:

\[
(MSK,\,
K_{sel},\,
K_{master},\,
sk_{DO},\,
\{sk_\ell\}_{\ell=1}^{n}).
\]

Each authorized user securely receives

\[
(SK_{\mathcal A},\,K_{sel}),
\]

whereas the Edge Gateway securely stores

\[
(K_{sel},\,sk_{DO}),
\]

and each Threshold Decryption Authority securely stores its
own threshold decryption share

\[
sk_\ell.
\]

Consequently, no user, sensor, cloud server, or individual
Threshold Decryption Authority possesses sufficient
information to decrypt aggregation ciphertexts
independently. Only the cooperation of at least \(t\)
Threshold Decryption Authorities enables successful
aggregate decryption.

\subsubsection*{\textbf{Phase 2 --- Sensor-Side Encryption and Edge-Side Authenticated Index Construction}}

This phase transforms sensor readings into authenticated
searchable structures while preserving confidentiality.
The resulting index supports secure conjunctive range search,
encrypted aggregation, and blockchain-verifiable integrity.


\paragraph*{Step 1: Sensor-Side Encryption}

For each sensor record

\[
D=(m,k,t,v),
\]

the sensor locally derives the canonical interval
identifier \(u_j\) for each searchable dimension
\(D_j\) from the plaintext value according to the public
canonical range-cover tree and constructs the authenticated
indexing metadata

\[
Meta_i=\{(D_j,u_j)\}_{j=1}^{d}.
\]

The sensor then encrypts the complete record using AES-GCM
with a unique 96-bit nonce \(N_i\) to obtain
\(CT_{AES}^{(i)}\), and encrypts the numerical value
\(v_i\) using Threshold EC-ElGamal to produce
\(CT_v^{(i)}\). Next, it increments the sequence number
\(seq_i\) and constructs the authenticated payload

\[
\mathcal P_i
=
(
ID_i,
seq_i,
N_i,
CT_{AES}^{(i)},
CT_v^{(i)},
Meta_i,
Tag_i
),
\]

where

\[
Tag_i
=
\textsf{HMAC}_{K_{HMAC}^{(i)}}
\Bigl(
ID_i
\parallel
seq_i
\parallel
N_i
\parallel
CT_{AES}^{(i)}
\parallel
CT_v^{(i)}
\parallel
Meta_i
\Bigr).
\]

Finally, the sensor transmits
\(\mathcal P_i\) to the Edge Gateway. Consequently, the
Edge Gateway constructs the authenticated searchable index
using only the authenticated indexing metadata
\(Meta_i\) without decrypting the sensor record or
aggregation ciphertext.

\paragraph*{Step 2: Edge-Side Verification}

Upon receiving

\[
\mathcal P_i
=
(
ID_i,
seq_i,
N_i,
CT_{AES}^{(i)},
CT_v^{(i)},
Meta_i,
Tag_i
),
\]

the Edge Gateway verifies

\begin{equation}
Tag_i
\stackrel{?}{=}
\textsf{HMAC}_{K_{HMAC}^{(i)}}
\Bigl(
ID_i
\parallel
seq_i
\parallel
N_i
\parallel
CT_{AES}^{(i)}
\parallel
CT_v^{(i)}
\parallel
Meta_i
\Bigr),
\end{equation}

and checks the freshness condition

\[
seq_i>seq_i^{last}.
\]

If both checks succeed, the gateway validates that every
\((D_j,u_j)\in Meta_i\) corresponds to a valid searchable
dimension and canonical node, updates

\[
seq_i^{last}
\leftarrow
seq_i,
\]

and forwards

\[
(
CT_{AES}^{(i)},
CT_v^{(i)},
Meta_i
)
\]

to the authenticated index-construction procedure. The
Edge Gateway constructs the authenticated searchable index
using only the authenticated indexing metadata
\(Meta_i\) supplied by the sensor; it neither derives
canonical nodes from plaintext sensor values nor decrypts
\(CT_{AES}^{(i)}\) or \(CT_v^{(i)}\).

\paragraph*{Step 3: Searchable Node Construction}

For each canonical node \(u\in\mathcal P_v^{(i)}\) within
searchable dimension \(D_j\), the Edge Gateway computes

\begin{equation}
\tau_u^{struct}
=
H_g(l_u\parallel r_u),
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
\tau_u^{ctx}
=
F(K_{sel},D_j\parallel u),
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
\tau_u
=
H_g(\tau_u^{struct}\parallel\tau_u^{ctx}).
\end{equation}

The corresponding protected bitmap is generated as

\begin{equation}
\widetilde B_u
=
B_u
\oplus
F(K_{sel},e\parallel D_j\parallel u),
\end{equation}

where \(e\) denotes the current index epoch. All bitmaps are
aligned over the global record space, with the \(i\)-th bit
corresponding to record identifier \(rid_i\), enabling direct
bitwise conjunction during conjunctive range evaluation.

The bitmap commitment is computed as

\begin{equation}
\sigma_u^{bmp}
=
H(u\parallel\widetilde B_u),
\end{equation}

and the searchable tag is encrypted under access policy
\(\mathcal P\):

\begin{equation}
CT_u^{tag}
=
\mathsf{ABSE.Enc}(PP,\tau_u,\mathcal P).
\end{equation}

Finally, the authenticated searchable-node commitment is
constructed as

\begin{equation}
\sigma_u
=
H\!\left(
u
\parallel
CT_u^{tag}
\parallel
\sigma_u^{bmp}
\parallel
e
\right),
\end{equation}

which cryptographically binds the canonical node, encrypted
searchable tag, bitmap commitment, and epoch into a single
Merkle-tree leaf for authenticated index construction.

\paragraph*{Step 4: Aggregation Metadata Registration}

For each record \(r_i\), the gateway registers

\begin{equation}
\mathcal A_i
=
\Bigl(
rid_i,
CT_v^{(i)},
Enc^{AHE}_{pk_{AHE}}(1)
\Bigr),
\end{equation}

where \(rid_i\) denotes the record identifier.

These encrypted metadata entries are later selected
according to the final conjunctive bitmap \(B_Q\),
ensuring that each matched record contributes exactly once
during aggregation.

\paragraph*{Step 5: Authenticated Commitment Construction}

At the end of epoch \(e\), the Edge Gateway constructs

\begin{equation}
Root_e^{idx}
=
\textsf{MerkleRoot}
\bigl(
\{\sigma_u\}
\bigr),
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
Root_e^{agg}
=
\textsf{MerkleRoot}
\bigl(
\{\mathcal A_i\}
\bigr),
\end{equation}

and

\begin{equation}
Root_e^{bmp}
=
\textsf{MerkleRoot}
\bigl(
\{\sigma_u^{bmp}\}
\bigr).
\end{equation}

The epoch commitment is computed as

\begin{equation}
Root_e
=
H
\Bigl(
Root_e^{idx}
\parallel
Root_e^{agg}
\parallel
Root_e^{bmp}
\parallel
e
\Bigr).
\end{equation}

The gateway then computes the signing digest

\begin{equation}
m_e
=
H
\Bigl(
Root_e
\parallel
ts
\Bigr),
\end{equation}

and generates the digital signature

\begin{equation}
\sigma_{DO}
=
\mathsf{DS.Sign}_{sk_{DO}}
\bigl(
m_e
\bigr),
\end{equation}

where \(\mathsf{DS}\) denotes the ECDSA signature scheme
over the secp256k1 elliptic curve with SHA-256.
Finally, the authenticated epoch state

\[
\bigl(
e,
Root_e,
ts,
\sigma_{DO}
\bigr)
\]

is anchored on the blockchain.

\paragraph*{Step 6: Secure Outsourcing}

The gateway outsources

\begin{equation}
\Bigl\{
CT_{AES}^{(i)},
CT_u^{tag},
\widetilde B_u,
\mathcal A_i,
\sigma_u,
\sigma_u^{bmp}
\Bigr\}
\end{equation}

to the cloud server.
Consequently, the cloud can recover \(B_u\) during authorized query
processing using the selector-derived mask, but learns no
plaintext sensor values.



\subsubsection*{\textbf{Phase 3 --- Conjunctive Range-Query Trapdoor Generation}}

An authorized user possessing attribute key
\(SK_{\mathcal A}\) locally generates a conjunctive
range-query trapdoor without revealing the queried
dimensions or numerical ranges.

\paragraph*{Step 1: Canonical Range Decomposition}

A conjunctive query is defined as

\begin{equation}
Q
=
\bigwedge_{j=1}^{d}
(D_j,[a_j,b_j]).
\end{equation}

For each searchable dimension \(D_j\), the user
decomposes the query interval into the minimal canonical
range-cover set

\begin{equation}
\mathcal C_j
=
\{u_{j,1},\ldots,u_{j,\ell_j}\},
\qquad
\ell_j
=
O(\log |D_j|).
\end{equation}

\paragraph*{Step 2: Search Token Generation}

For every canonical node
\(u_{j,i}\in\mathcal C_j\), the user reconstructs the
searchable tag

\begin{equation}
\tau_{u_{j,i}}
=
H_g
\!\left(
H_g(l_u\!\parallel\! r_u)
\parallel
F(K_{sel},D_j\!\parallel\!u_{j,i})
\right),
\end{equation}

randomizes it as

\begin{equation}
\tau'_{u_{j,i}}
=
\tau_{u_{j,i}}
g^{r_{j,i}},
\qquad
r_{j,i}
\xleftarrow{\$}
\mathbb Z_p,
\end{equation}

and generates the attribute-bound search token

\begin{equation}
Tok_{j,i}
=
\textsf{ABSE.TokenGen}
(
SK_{\mathcal A},
\tau'_{u_{j,i}}
).
\end{equation}

\paragraph*{Step 3: Node-Selector Generation}

For each canonical node, the user derives the
epoch-dependent bitmap selector

\begin{equation}
Sel_{j,i}
=
F
(
K_{sel},
e
\parallel
D_j
\parallel
u_{j,i}
),
\end{equation}

where \(e\) denotes the latest finalized index epoch.
The selector enables recovery of only the matched bitmap

\begin{equation}
B_u
=
\widetilde B_u
\oplus
Sel_{j,i},
\end{equation}

without revealing the secret selector seed
\(K_{sel}\).

\paragraph*{Step 4: Trapdoor Construction}

The final query trapdoor is

\begin{equation}
T_Q
=
\Bigl\{
(
Tok_{j,i},
g^{r_{j,i}},
Sel_{j,i}
)
\Bigr\},
\qquad
u_{j,i}\in\mathcal C_j,
\end{equation}

whose size is

\begin{equation}
|T_Q|
=
O
\!\left(
\sum_{j=1}^{d}
\log |D_j|
\right).
\end{equation}

\subsubsection*{\textbf{Phase 4 --- Verifiable Conjunctive Range Search and Aggregation}}

Using trapdoor \(T_Q\), the cloud performs searchable
matching, conjunctive bitmap filtering, encrypted
aggregation, and verifiable proof generation without
learning query contents or plaintext sensor data.

\paragraph*{Step 1: Searchable Node Matching and Metadata Retrieval}

For each queried dimension \(D_j\), the authorized user
includes the query-specific node selectors
\(\{Sel_{j,i}\}\), generated using the derived selector key
\(K_s'\), in the query trapdoor \(T_Q\). Upon receiving
\(T_Q\), the cloud identifies the matched canonical nodes

\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal M_j
=
\Bigl\{
u
\;\Big|\;
&
\textsf{ABSE.Match}
\bigl(
Tok_{j,i},
\\
&
CT_u^{tag}
\bigr)
=
1
\Bigr\}.
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}

Since the canonical range-cover decomposition for each
query interval is deterministic, the expected
canonical-node set is uniquely determined during trapdoor
generation. Accordingly, the cloud must return the complete
matched node set \(\mathcal M_j\). During query
verification, the user reconstructs the expected canonical
range cover and verifies that the returned node set is in
one-to-one correspondence with the expected decomposition.
Any omission, substitution, or insertion of canonical nodes
is therefore detected before bitmap recovery and
aggregation.

For each matched node
\(u\in\mathcal M_j\),
the cloud retrieves the associated protected bitmap,
authenticated searchable-node commitment, bitmap
commitment, and aggregation metadata

\[
\Bigl(
\widetilde B_u,
\sigma_u,
\sigma_u^{bmp},
\mathcal A_i
\Bigr),
\]

where

\[
\mathcal A_i
=
\Bigl(
rid_i,
CT_v^{(i)},
Enc^{AHE}_{pk_{AHE}}(1)
\Bigr).
\]

Using the query-specific selectors contained in \(T_Q\),
the cloud performs the subsequent bitmap-recovery
operations without learning the long-term selector secret
\(K_s\) or the derived selector key \(K_s'\).

\paragraph*{Step 2: Conjunctive Bitmap Filtering}

For each matched canonical node \(u\in\mathcal M_j\), the
cloud recovers the corresponding bitmap by removing the
protected mask using the node-specific selector contained in
the query trapdoor:

\begin{equation}
B_u
=
\widetilde B_u
\oplus
Sel_{j,i}.
\end{equation}

Since the selector is generated exclusively for the queried
canonical node, the cloud can recover only the bitmaps
required for the authorized query without learning the secret
bitmap-selector seed.

All protected bitmaps are constructed over the same global
record space. Consequently, every recovered bitmap \(B_u\)
has identical length \(N_e\), where \(N_e\) denotes the total
number of indexed records in epoch \(e\), and the \(i\)-th bit
of every bitmap corresponds to the same global record
identifier \(rid_i\). Therefore, bitwise OR and AND
operations are performed directly over aligned bitmaps
without requiring additional index transformation.

For each queried dimension \(D_j\), the cloud computes the
dimension-level candidate bitmap

\begin{equation}
B_{D_j}
=
\bigvee_{u\in\mathcal M_j}
B_u.
\end{equation}

The final conjunctive bitmap is

\begin{equation}
B_Q
=
\bigwedge_{j=1}^{d}
B_{D_j}.
\end{equation}

A record identifier \(r_i\) is selected if and only if

\begin{equation}
B_Q[i]
=
1.
\end{equation}

Accordingly, the matched record set is

\begin{equation}
\mathcal R_Q
=
\{\,r_i \mid B_Q[i]=1\,\}.
\end{equation}

Since the canonical range-cover decomposition is
deterministic and every recovered bitmap corresponds to an
authenticated canonical node satisfying the query predicate,
the resulting bitmap \(B_Q\) uniquely represents the records
that satisfy the conjunctive range query. Consequently,
\(\mathcal R_Q\) is uniquely determined by the verified bitmap
and serves as the exclusive input to the subsequent
homomorphic aggregation procedure.

The matched canonical-node set retained for proof generation
is

\begin{equation}
\mathcal U_Q
=
\bigcup_{j=1}^{d}
\mathcal M_j.
\end{equation}
\paragraph*{Step 3: Bitmap-Constrained Homomorphic Aggregation}

The verified query bitmap \(B_Q\) uniquely determines the
matched record set

\begin{equation}
\mathcal R_Q
=
\{\,r_i \mid B_Q[i]=1\,\}.
\end{equation}

The cloud performs homomorphic aggregation exclusively over
the authenticated aggregation metadata associated with
records in \(\mathcal R_Q\). Specifically, the aggregate
ciphertexts are computed as

\begin{equation}
CT_{sum}
=
\bigoplus_{r_i\in\mathcal R_Q}
CT_v^{(i)},
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
CT_{count}
=
\bigoplus_{r_i\in\mathcal R_Q}
Enc^{AHE}_{pk_{AHE}}(1).
\end{equation}

Since \(\mathcal R_Q\) is uniquely determined by the
verified bitmap \(B_Q\), each matched record contributes
exactly once to both \(CT_{sum}\) and \(CT_{count}\),
thereby eliminating duplicate counting caused by
overlapping canonical nodes. Consequently, no ciphertext
outside the verified record set \(\mathcal R_Q\)
participates in the aggregation.

The aggregate ciphertexts remain encrypted under the
Threshold EC-ElGamal public key \(pk_{AHE}\) and are
subsequently decrypted only through the cooperation of at
least \(t\) TDAs after the
authenticated query response has been successfully
verified.

\paragraph*{Step 4: Verifiable Result Construction and Return}

For every matched canonical node
\(u\in\mathcal U_Q\), the cloud generates the searchable-node
Merkle proof

\begin{equation}
\pi_u
=
\textsf{MerkleProof}
\bigl(
\sigma_u,
Root_e^{idx}
\bigr),
\end{equation}

and the bitmap-commitment Merkle proof

\begin{equation}
\pi_u^{bmp}
=
\textsf{MerkleProof}
\bigl(
\sigma_u^{bmp},
Root_e^{bmp}
\bigr).
\end{equation}

The cloud then constructs the authenticated batch
commitment

\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
\Pi_{batch}
=
H\Bigl(
&
Acc_e
\parallel
Root_e^{agg}
\\
&
\parallel
H(\{\sigma_u\}_{u\in\mathcal U_Q})
\\
&
\parallel
H(\{\sigma_u^{bmp}\}_{u\in\mathcal U_Q})
\\
&
\parallel
H(B_Q)
\\
&
\parallel
CT_{sum}
\parallel
CT_{count}
\Bigr).
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}

which binds the authenticated searchable nodes,
bitmap commitments, conjunctive bitmap, aggregation
ciphertexts, and blockchain-anchored aggregation state into
a single verifiable proof.

Finally, the cloud returns

\begin{equation}
\mathcal Rsp_Q
=
\Bigl(
CT_{sum},
CT_{count},
B_Q,
\Pi_{batch},
\{\sigma_u\}_{u\in\mathcal U_Q},
\{\sigma_u^{bmp}\}_{u\in\mathcal U_Q},
\{\pi_u\}_{u\in\mathcal U_Q},
\{\pi_u^{bmp}\}_{u\in\mathcal U_Q},
Root_e
\Bigr).
\end{equation}

If record retrieval is requested, the corresponding encrypted
records

\[
CT_{AES}^{(i)},
\qquad
r_i\in\mathcal R_Q,
\]

are also included in the response.


\subsubsection*{\textbf{Phase 5 --- Blockchain-Anchored Verification and Threshold Decryption}}

Upon receiving

\[
\begin{aligned}
Rsp_Q
=
\Bigl(
&
e,
CT_{sum},
CT_{count},
B_Q,
\mathcal R_Q,
\Pi_{batch},
\\
&
\{\sigma_u\},
\{\sigma_u^{bmp}\},
\{\pi_u\},
\{\pi_u^{bmp}\},
Root_e,
\{CT_{K_i}\}
\Bigr),
\end{aligned}
\]

the user first verifies the authenticity, integrity,
completeness, and freshness of the returned query result
before performing threshold aggregate decryption or
optional record decryption.

\paragraph*{Step 1: Blockchain and Query-State Verification}

The user retrieves the authenticated state

\[
State_e
=
(
e,
Root_e^{idx},
Root_e^{agg},
Root_e^{bmp},
Root_e,
ts,
\sigma_{DO}
)
\]

from the blockchain, verifies

\begin{equation}
\mathsf{DS.Verify}_{pk_{DO}}
\bigl(
H(Root_e\parallel ts),
\sigma_{DO}
\bigr)
=
1,
\end{equation}

and confirms that \(e\) is the latest finalized epoch.
The user reconstructs the canonical range cover from the
query trapdoor, verifies that the returned canonical-node
set matches the expected decomposition, validates all
Merkle proofs against
\(Root_e^{idx}\)
and
\(Root_e^{bmp}\),
and recomputes

\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
\Pi_{batch}^{*}
=
H\Bigl(
&
Root_e
\parallel
H(\{\sigma_u\})
\\
&
\parallel
H(\{\sigma_u^{bmp}\})
\parallel
H(B_Q)
\\
&
\parallel
H(\mathcal R_Q)
\parallel
CT_{sum}
\parallel
CT_{count}
\Bigr).
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}

The response is accepted for decryption only if

\[
\Pi_{batch}^{*}
=
\Pi_{batch}.
\]
Successful verification confirms the authenticity,
integrity, completeness, and freshness of the authenticated
query state, and cryptographically binds the returned
aggregation ciphertexts
\((CT_{sum},CT_{count})\)
to the verified bitmap
\(B_Q\)
and matched record set
\(\mathcal R_Q\).
\paragraph*{Step 2: Threshold Aggregate Decryption}

After successful verification, the user submits
\((CT_{sum},CT_{count})\) to a set
\(S\) of Threshold Decryption Authorities satisfying
\(|S|\ge t\). Each authority
\(\ell\in S\) computes

\[
\delta_\ell^{sum}
=
sk_\ell C_1^{sum},
\qquad
\delta_\ell^{count}
=
sk_\ell C_1^{count},
\]

which are verified using the corresponding public
verification keys. The user reconstructs

\[
D_{sum}
=
\sum_{\ell\in S}
\lambda_\ell
\delta_\ell^{sum},
\qquad
D_{count}
=
\sum_{\ell\in S}
\lambda_\ell
\delta_\ell^{count},
\]

and recovers

\[
M_{sum}
=
C_2^{sum}
-
D_{sum},
\qquad
M_{count}
=
C_2^{count}
-
D_{count}.
\]

Finally,

\[
Sum
=
\mathsf{BSGS}(M_{sum}),
\qquad
Count
=
\mathsf{BSGS}(M_{count}),
\]

and

\[
Avg
=
\frac{Sum}{Count},
\qquad
Count>0.
\]

\paragraph*{Step 3: Optional Record Decryption}

During data outsourcing, the Edge Gateway generates an
ABSE-protected key envelope

\[
CT_{K_i}
=
\textsf{ABSE.Enc}
(PP,
K_{AES}^{(i)},
\mathcal P).
\]

For record-retrieval queries, each returned
\(CT_{AES}^{(i)}\) is accompanied by
\(CT_{K_i}\). A user whose attributes satisfy
\(\mathcal P\) recovers
\(K_{AES}^{(i)}\) and decrypts

\[
D_i
=
\textsf{AES\mbox{-}GCM.Dec}
(K_{AES}^{(i)},
CT_{AES}^{(i)}).
\]

The AES-GCM authentication tag provides end-to-end record
integrity and authenticity. The query result is accepted
only if blockchain verification, canonical-cover
verification, Merkle-proof validation, authenticated batch
verification, and the requested decryption operation(s)
complete successfully; otherwise, the response is rejected.

\section{Security Analysis}

\subsection{Security Model}

We consider a probabilistic polynomial-time (PPT)
adversary \(\mathcal A\) that controls the cloud server
and communication channels. During normal protocol
execution, the Edge Gateway is assumed to be
honest-but-curious and faithfully performs sensor
authentication, authenticated index construction,
aggregation-metadata generation, and blockchain
commitment, while attempting to infer information only
from the permitted leakage.

The adversary observes encrypted records, searchable
ciphertexts, protected bitmaps, aggregation metadata,
query trapdoors, Merkle proofs, authenticated batch
commitments, blockchain states, and the leakage function
\(\mathcal L_{BVCRSA}\). It may adaptively issue
ciphertext, trapdoor, aggregation, and verification
queries, and may attempt to infer plaintext information
beyond the permitted leakage, generate unauthorized
trapdoors, omit, modify, replay, or fabricate query
responses, or forge verification proofs.

The adversary does not possess the ABSE master secret
\(MSK\), the long-term bitmap-selector secret
\(K_s\), the Edge Gateway signing key
\(sk_{DO}\), any unauthorized attribute secret key, or
the threshold decryption shares
\(\{sk_\ell\}_{\ell=1}^{n}\). The query-specific selector
key

\[
K_s'
=
H(K_s\parallel e_q)
\]

is deterministically derived only by authorized users
during trapdoor generation and is never disclosed to the
Edge Gateway or the cloud. We assume that fewer than
\(t\) Threshold Decryption Authorities (TDAs) may be
corrupted; consequently, the threshold decryption key
cannot be reconstructed and aggregation ciphertexts
remain confidential. Detecting or tolerating a malicious
Edge Gateway that intentionally anchors incorrect
authenticated states before blockchain commitment is
outside the scope of this work.

The security objective of BVCRSA is to guarantee

\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
&
\mathsf{Privacy}
\wedge
\mathsf{Confidentiality}
\wedge
\mathsf{AntiCollusion}
\\
&
{}\wedge
\mathsf{QueryStateIntegrity}
\wedge
\mathsf{QueryStateCompleteness}
\wedge
\mathsf{Freshness},
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}

while revealing only the leakage explicitly specified by
\(\mathcal L_{BVCRSA}\). In particular, BVCRSA
cryptographically authenticates that the returned
aggregation ciphertexts correspond to the verified
matched record set and authenticated query state, but it
does not claim general verifiable computation for
arbitrary homomorphic operations.
\subsection{Leakage Function}

BVCRSA follows the standard adaptive searchable-encryption
leakage model and reveals only the structural information
necessary for encrypted query processing.

The overall leakage profile is defined as

\begin{equation}
\mathcal L_{BVCRSA}
=
\Bigl(
\mathcal L_{\mathsf{Setup}},
\mathcal L_{\mathsf{Data}},
\mathcal L_{\mathsf{Query}},
\mathcal L_{\mathsf{Access}}
\Bigr).
\end{equation}

\paragraph*{Setup Leakage.}

The setup phase reveals only the public parameters

\begin{equation}
\mathcal L_{\mathsf{Setup}}
=
PP.
\end{equation}

No master secret keys, attribute secret keys, aggregation
private keys, bitmap-selector seed, or signing keys are
disclosed.

\paragraph*{Data Leakage.}

For each outsourced record, the cloud learns

\begin{equation}
\mathcal L_{\mathsf{Data}}
=
\Bigl(
|CT_{AES}|,
|CT_v|,
|\mathcal P_v|
\Bigr),
\end{equation}

where \(|CT_{AES}|\) and \(|CT_v|\) denote the ciphertext
sizes and \(|\mathcal P_v|\) denotes the number of canonical
range-cover nodes associated with the record.

\paragraph*{Query Leakage.}

For each query, the cloud learns

\begin{equation}
\mathcal L_{\mathsf{Query}}
=
\Bigl(
|T_Q|,
Pat_Q
\Bigr),
\end{equation}

where \(Pat_Q\) denotes the search pattern indicating whether
two trapdoors generate identical matched-node sets.

\paragraph*{Access Leakage.}

During query execution, the cloud observes

\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal L_{\mathsf{Access}}
=
\Bigl(
&
\mathcal U_Q,
\{B_u\},
B_Q,
\\
&
\mathcal R_Q,
|\mathcal R_Q|
\Bigr),
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}

where

\begin{itemize}
\item \(\mathcal U_Q\) denotes the matched canonical-node set;
\item \(\{B_u\}\) denotes the recovered canonical-node bitmaps;
\item \(B_Q\) denotes the conjunctive query bitmap;
\item \(\mathcal R_Q\) denotes the matched record set;
\item \(|\mathcal R_Q|\) denotes the query-result cardinality.
\end{itemize}

For consistency with standard searchable-encryption
terminology, we define

\begin{equation}
\mathsf{SearchPattern}
=
Pat_Q,
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
\mathsf{AccessPattern}
=
\Bigl(
\mathcal U_Q,
\mathcal R_Q
\Bigr),
\end{equation}

and

\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
\mathsf{SizePattern}
=
\Bigl(
&
|CT_{AES}|,
|CT_v|,
|\mathcal P_v|,
\\
&
|T_Q|,
|\mathcal U_Q|,
|\mathcal R_Q|
\Bigr).
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}

Accordingly,

\begin{equation}
\mathcal L_{BVCRSA}
=
\Bigl(
PP,
\mathsf{SizePattern},
\mathsf{SearchPattern},
\mathsf{AccessPattern}
\Bigr),
\end{equation}

or equivalently,

\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal L_{BVCRSA}
=
\Bigl(
&
PP,
|CT_{AES}|,
|CT_v|,
|\mathcal P_v|,
\\
&
|T_Q|,
Pat_Q,
\mathcal U_Q,
\{B_u\},
\\
&
B_Q,
\mathcal R_Q,
|\mathcal R_Q|
\Bigr).
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}

Beyond the information explicitly captured by
\(\mathcal L_{BVCRSA}\), BVCRSA reveals no additional
information regarding plaintext sensor records, plaintext
numerical values, queried numerical ranges, searchable
dimensions, homomorphic decryption results, bitmap-selector
secrets, aggregation private keys, or authenticated
query-state signing keys.

The leakage specified by
\(\mathcal L_{BVCRSA}\)
reflects the practical tradeoff adopted by most
searchable-encryption schemes. An honest-but-curious cloud
may correlate repeated or overlapping queries through the
revealed matched canonical nodes, bitmap intersections,
accessed records, and result cardinality, thereby inferring
coarse information such as query selectivity or data
distribution. Representative searchable-encryption schemes
(e.g., Refs.~\cite{ref39,ref40,ref41,ref44}) likewise reveal
search and access patterns, although the exact leakage
profiles differ according to their constructions. BVCRSA
further reveals authenticated canonical-node and bitmap
information to enable query-state completeness verification
and encrypted aggregation without relying on ORAM,
zero-knowledge proofs, or trusted hardware.

\subsection{Theorem 1: Conjunctive Query Privacy}

\textbf{Theorem 1.}
Assuming the adaptive security of ABSE and the
pseudorandomness of
\(F(K_s',\cdot)\), BVCRSA preserves conjunctive query
privacy against probabilistic polynomial-time adversaries,
revealing no information beyond the leakage function
\(\mathcal L_{BVCRSA}\).

\textbf{Proof.}

We prove the theorem through a sequence of games.

\textbf{Game \(G_0\).}
The adversary observes the real execution of BVCRSA,
including searchable ciphertexts, query tokens, node
selectors, authenticated batch commitments, Merkle proofs,
and blockchain states.

\textbf{Game \(G_1\).}
Replace each node selector

\begin{equation}
Sel_{j,i}
=
F
\bigl(
K_s',
D_j
\parallel
u_{j,i}
\bigr)
\end{equation}

with a uniformly random value of the same length.
Distinguishing \(G_1\) from \(G_0\) breaks the
pseudorandomness of
\(F(K_s',\cdot)\). Therefore,

\begin{equation}
\left|
Pr[G_1]-Pr[G_0]
\right|
\le
Adv_{\mathcal A}^{PRF}(\lambda).
\end{equation}

\textbf{Game \(G_2\).}
Replace the ABSE searchable ciphertexts and query tokens
with simulated values generated solely from the leakage
function
\(\mathcal L_{BVCRSA}\).
By the adaptive security of ABSE,

\begin{equation}
\left|
Pr[G_2]-Pr[G_1]
\right|
\le
Adv_{\mathcal A}^{ABSE}(\lambda).
\end{equation}

Hence, the adversary's view in \(G_2\) is completely
determined by
\(\mathcal L_{BVCRSA}\), revealing no additional
information regarding plaintext sensor records, queried
numerical ranges, searchable dimensions, homomorphic
decryption results, or secret cryptographic material.

Therefore,

\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
Adv_{\mathcal A}^{CQ}
\le {}&
Adv_{\mathcal A}^{PRF}(\lambda)
+
Adv_{\mathcal A}^{ABSE}(\lambda)
\\
&
+
negl(\lambda).
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}

Hence, BVCRSA preserves conjunctive query privacy under
the leakage function
\(\mathcal L_{BVCRSA}\).
\hfill\(\square\)

\subsection{Theorem 2: Confidentiality of Outsourced IIoT Sensor Data}

\textbf{Theorem 2.}
Assuming the IND-CPA security of AES-GCM and Threshold
EC-ElGamal, BVCRSA preserves the confidentiality of
outsourced IIoT sensor data against probabilistic
polynomial-time adversaries, revealing no information
beyond the leakage function
\(\mathcal L_{BVCRSA}\).

\textbf{Proof.}

Each sensor record

\[
D_i=(m_i,k_i,t_i,v_i)
\]

is encrypted using AES-GCM as

\begin{equation}
CT_{AES}^{(i)}
=
\textsf{AES\mbox{-}GCM.Enc}
\bigl(
K_{AES}^{(i)},
D_i
\bigr),
\end{equation}

which is computationally indistinguishable from random
under the IND-CPA security of AES-GCM.

The numerical value \(v_i\) is independently encrypted
using Threshold EC-ElGamal as

\begin{equation}
CT_v^{(i)}
=
(r_iG,\,
v_iG+r_iP),
\end{equation}

where

\[
r_i
\xleftarrow{\$}
\mathbb Z_p^{*}.
\]

The corresponding decryption key is distributed among
\(n\) Threshold Decryption Authorities using Shamir secret
sharing. Under the assumption that fewer than \(t\)
authorities are corrupted, neither the cloud nor any
coalition of unauthorized users and fewer than \(t\) TDAs
can reconstruct the decryption key or recover the
underlying plaintext values.

Consequently, an adversary learns only the information
explicitly specified by
\(\mathcal L_{BVCRSA}\), while the confidentiality of both
encrypted sensor records and aggregation ciphertexts is
preserved. Therefore,

\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
Adv_{\mathcal A}^{Conf}
\le {}&
Adv_{\mathcal A}^{AES}(\lambda)
\\
&
+
Adv_{\mathcal A}^{T\text{-}ECElGamal}(\lambda)
+
negl(\lambda),
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}

where
\(Adv_{\mathcal A}^{AES}(\lambda)\)
and
\(Adv_{\mathcal A}^{T\text{-}ECElGamal}(\lambda)\)
denote the IND-CPA advantages against AES-GCM and
Threshold EC-ElGamal, respectively. Hence, BVCRSA
preserves the confidentiality of outsourced IIoT sensor
data.
\hfill\(\square\)

\subsection{Theorem 3: Threshold Aggregate-Decryption Security}

\textbf{Theorem 3.}
Assuming the IND-CPA security of Threshold EC-ElGamal,
no probabilistic polynomial-time adversary controlling the
cloud server, unauthorized users, and fewer than \(t\)
Threshold Decryption Authorities can recover the plaintext
of an aggregate ciphertext or reconstruct the aggregation
private key.

\textbf{Proof.}

Let

\[
CT=(C_1,C_2)
\]

denote an aggregate ciphertext encrypted under the public
key \(pk_{AHE}\). The corresponding private key is shared
among \(n\) Threshold Decryption Authorities using a
\((t,n)\)-threshold secret-sharing scheme, where each
authority stores only its secret share \(sk_\ell\).

For decryption, each participating authority computes the
partial decryption

\begin{equation}
\delta_\ell
=
sk_\ell C_1.
\end{equation}

After collecting at least \(t\) valid partial decryptions,
the user reconstructs

\begin{equation}
D
=
\sum_{\ell\in S}
\lambda_\ell
\delta_\ell,
\qquad
|S|\ge t,
\end{equation}

where \(\lambda_\ell\) denotes the corresponding Lagrange
coefficient. The plaintext group element is then recovered
as

\begin{equation}
M
=
C_2-D.
\end{equation}

Since fewer than \(t\) secret shares reveal no information
about the underlying decryption key, neither the cloud nor
any coalition of unauthorized users and fewer than \(t\)
Threshold Decryption Authorities can reconstruct the
private key or decrypt aggregate ciphertexts. Moreover,
partial decryptions are generated only after successful
verification of the authenticated query response in
Phase~5, preventing unauthorized decryption requests.

Therefore,

\begin{equation}
Adv_{\mathcal A}^{TDec}
\le
Adv_{\mathcal A}^{T\text{-}ECElGamal}(\lambda)
+
negl(\lambda).
\end{equation}

Hence, BVCRSA preserves threshold-secure aggregate
decryption.
\hfill\(\square\)

\subsection{Theorem 4: Anti-Collusion Security}

\textbf{Theorem 4.}
Colluding users cannot generate valid search trapdoors for unauthorized
conjunctive range queries unless their combined attributes satisfy the
embedded access policy.

\textbf{Proof.}

For every searchable node, the corresponding search token is generated as

\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
Tok_{j,i} = {} & \textsf{ABSE.TokenGen} \left( SK_{\mathcal A}, \tau_{u_{j,i}} \right),
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}

where \(SK_{\mathcal A}\) is the attribute secret key associated with
attribute set \(\mathcal A\).

A valid token can be generated only when the user's attribute set
satisfies the access policy

\begin{equation}
\mathcal A
\models
\mathcal P.
\end{equation}

Suppose multiple users collude by combining attribute secret keys

\begin{equation}
SK_{\mathcal A_1},
SK_{\mathcal A_2},
\ldots,
SK_{\mathcal A_t}.
\end{equation}

Under the anti-collusion property of ABSE, secret-key components are
cryptographically bound to their originating users and cannot be
combined to construct a valid key for an unauthorized attribute set.

Consequently, the colluding users cannot generate a valid token

\begin{equation}
Tok_{j,i}^{*}
\end{equation}

for any policy that is not individually satisfied.

Therefore,

\begin{equation}
Adv_{\mathcal A}^{Coll}
\le
Adv_{\mathcal A}^{ABSE}
+
negl(\lambda).
\end{equation}

Hence, BVCRSA achieves anti-collusion security.
\subsection{Theorem 5: Aggregation Correctness}

\textbf{Theorem 5.}
The aggregate ciphertexts are computed exclusively over the
records satisfying all queried range predicates, with each
matched record contributing exactly once.

\textbf{Proof.}

For each queried dimension \(D_j\), the cloud identifies the
matched canonical-node set

\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal M_j
=
\Bigl\{
u
\;\Big|\;
&
\textsf{ABSE.Match}
(
Tok_{j,i},
\\
&
CT_u^{tag}
)
=
1
\Bigr\}.
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}

The corresponding dimension-level bitmap is obtained by

\begin{equation}
B_{D_j}
=
\bigvee_{u\in\mathcal M_j}
B_u,
\end{equation}

and the conjunctive bitmap is computed as

\begin{equation}
B_Q
=
\bigwedge_{j=1}^{d}
B_{D_j}.
\end{equation}

Hence,

\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
B_Q[i]=1
\iff
&
(D_1\in[a_1,b_1])
\\
&
\wedge\cdots\wedge
(D_d\in[a_d,b_d]),
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}

and the matched record set is uniquely determined as

\begin{equation}
\mathcal R_Q
=
\{\,r_i\mid B_Q[i]=1\,\}.
\end{equation}

The cloud performs homomorphic aggregation only over the
authenticated aggregation metadata associated with
\(\mathcal R_Q\):

\begin{equation}
CT_{sum}
=
\bigoplus_{r_i\in\mathcal R_Q}
CT_v^{(i)},
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
CT_{count}
=
\bigoplus_{r_i\in\mathcal R_Q}
Enc^{AHE}_{pk_{AHE}}(1).
\end{equation}

Since each record identifier appears at most once in
\(\mathcal R_Q\), every matched record contributes exactly
once to both aggregate ciphertexts, while no record outside
\(\mathcal R_Q\) participates in the aggregation.
Furthermore, the authenticated batch commitment binds
\((B_Q,\mathcal R_Q,CT_{sum},CT_{count})\), enabling the
user to verify in Phase~5 that the returned aggregate
ciphertexts correspond to the verified query result.

Therefore, the aggregate ciphertexts correctly represent
the sum and count of all records satisfying the conjunctive
range query.
\hfill\(\square\)
\subsection{Theorem 6: Verifiable Query-State Integrity}

\textbf{Theorem 6.}
A probabilistic polynomial-time adversary cannot forge,
modify, substitute, omit, or replay the authenticated
query state or the aggregation ciphertexts bound to that
state without detection, except with negligible
probability.

\textbf{Proof.}

For each epoch \(e\), the Edge Gateway computes

\begin{equation}
Root_e
=
H\!\left(
Root_e^{idx}
\parallel
Root_e^{agg}
\parallel
Root_e^{bmp}
\parallel
e
\right),
\end{equation}

computes

\begin{equation}
m_e
=
H(Root_e\parallel ts),
\end{equation}

and signs

\begin{equation}
\sigma_{DO}
=
\mathsf{DS.Sign}_{sk_{DO}}(m_e),
\end{equation}

before anchoring
\((e,Root_e,ts,\sigma_{DO})\)
on the blockchain.

For each query response, the cloud computes

\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
\Pi_{batch}
=
H\Bigl(
&
Root_e
\parallel
H(\{\sigma_u\})
\parallel
H(\{\sigma_u^{bmp}\})
\\
&
\parallel
H(B_Q)
\parallel
H(\mathcal R_Q)
\parallel
CT_{sum}
\parallel
CT_{count}
\Bigr).
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}

During verification, the user reconstructs the expected
canonical range cover from the submitted query,
verifies that the returned canonical-node set matches the
expected decomposition, validates the Merkle proofs for
the authenticated searchable-node and bitmap commitments,
and recomputes
\(\Pi_{batch}\).
Consequently, any modification, substitution, omission, or
replay of authenticated searchable nodes, bitmap
commitments, query-state commitments, aggregation
ciphertexts, or blockchain states changes either
\(Root_e\), \(m_e\), or \(\Pi_{batch}\), causing
verification failure. Replay attacks are prevented by
requiring the latest finalized blockchain epoch.

Therefore,

\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
Pr[\mathsf{Forge}]
\le {}&
Adv_{\mathcal A}^{\mathsf{ECDSA\mbox{-}EUF\mbox{-}CMA}}
(\lambda)
\\
&
+
Adv_{H}^{CR}(\lambda)
+
negl(\lambda),
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}

where a successful forgery requires either forging a valid
Edge Gateway signature or finding a collision in the hash
function \(H(\cdot)\). Hence, BVCRSA guarantees the
integrity, completeness, and freshness of the
blockchain-authenticated query state while
cryptographically binding the returned aggregation
ciphertexts to the verified matched record set and
authenticated query state. This theorem does not claim
general verifiable computation of homomorphic aggregation;
rather, it guarantees that any accepted aggregation
ciphertexts are authenticated with respect to the verified
query state.

\hfill\(\square\)

\subsection{Theorem 7: Cryptographic Query-Token Unlinkability}

\textbf{Theorem 7.}
Assuming the pseudorandomness of
\(F(K_s',\cdot)\) and the adaptive security of ABSE,
BVCRSA provides cryptographic unlinkability of
query-specific node selectors and randomized ABSE query
tokens across different query epochs, subject to the
leakage function
\(\mathcal L_{BVCRSA}\).

\textbf{Proof.}

For each query epoch \(e_q\), the authorized user derives
the query-specific selector key

\[
K_s'
=
H(K_s\parallel e_q),
\]

and computes the node selector

\begin{equation}
Sel_{j,i}
=
F
\Bigl(
K_s',
D_j
\parallel
u_{j,i}
\Bigr).
\end{equation}

Since \(K_s'\) is uniquely derived for each query epoch,
selectors generated for the same canonical node across
different epochs are computationally independent under the
pseudorandomness of
\(F(K_s',\cdot)\).

Furthermore, each ABSE query token is freshly randomized
during trapdoor generation. Under the adaptive security of
ABSE, these randomized tokens reveal no information beyond
the leakage function
\(\mathcal L_{BVCRSA}\).

Therefore, distinguishing whether two node selectors or
ABSE query tokens originate from the same query beyond the
permitted leakage would require either distinguishing
\(F(K_s',\cdot)\) from a random function or breaking the
adaptive security of ABSE. Hence,

\begin{equation}
Adv_{\mathcal A}^{Link}
\le
Adv_{\mathcal A}^{PRF}(\lambda)
+
Adv_{\mathcal A}^{ABSE}(\lambda)
+
negl(\lambda).
\end{equation}

Accordingly, BVCRSA provides cryptographic unlinkability
of query-specific node selectors and randomized ABSE query
tokens across different query epochs. However, repeated or
overlapping queries may still be correlated through the
search and access patterns explicitly permitted by
\(\mathcal L_{BVCRSA}\), including matched canonical-node
sets, recovered bitmaps, matched record sets, and query
result cardinalities.
\hfill\(\square\)

\subsection{Theorem 8: Query-State Freshness and Rollback Resistance}

\textbf{Theorem 8.}
A malicious cloud cannot successfully replay stale query states or rollback authenticated search results.

\textbf{Proof.}

For every epoch $e$, the blockchain stores the authenticated query state

\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
State_e = ( & e, Root_e^{idx}, Root_e^{agg}, Root_e^{bmp}, \\
& Acc_e, ts, \sigma_{DO} ).
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}

Before accepting a query result, the user verifies that the returned state corresponds to the latest finalized blockchain epoch.

Suppose the cloud returns a stale state $State_{e'}$ where

\begin{equation}
e'
<
e.
\end{equation}

The freshness verification immediately detects the existence of a newer finalized epoch and rejects the response.

Furthermore, any modification of

\begin{equation}
Root_e^{idx},
\quad
Root_e^{agg},
\quad
Root_e^{bmp}
\end{equation}

changes

\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
Acc_e = H \left( & Root_e^{idx} \parallel Root_e^{agg} \parallel Root_e^{bmp} \right),
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}

which invalidates the authenticated blockchain state.

Therefore, rollback succeeds only if blockchain finality or the collision resistance of $H(\cdot)$ is broken.

Hence,

\begin{equation}
Pr[\textsf{Rollback}]
\le
Adv_{BC}
+
Adv_H
+
negl(\lambda).
\end{equation}

Thus, BVCRSA achieves query-state freshness and rollback resistance.


\section{EVALUATION}

This section evaluates the complexity and performance of BVCRSA. The analysis covers index construction, trapdoor generation, query processing, aggregation, and verification costs. BVCRSA is compared with Trinity~\cite{ref39}, ABSE-Range~\cite{ref40}, Latt-IBEKS~\cite{ref41}, and VC-KASE~\cite{ref44}, which collectively represent state-of-the-art encrypted range search, attribute-based searchable encryption, post-quantum searchable encryption, and verifiable searchable data-sharing frameworks.


