As presented in Table~\ref{tab:complexity_comparison},
Scheme~\cite{ref38} and Trinity~\cite{ref39} support
efficient range-query processing through specialized
indexing structures; however, neither provides result
verification or encrypted aggregation.
Scheme~\cite{ref40} enables attribute-based range search,
but its trapdoor generation and query processing scale with
the number of searchable attributes and pairing operations.
Scheme~\cite{ref41} achieves post-quantum security using
lattice-based constructions, but incurs substantially higher
trapdoor-generation and search costs due to lattice sampling
and matrix computations. VC-KASE~\cite{ref44} supports
verifiable conjunctive keyword search with aggregate-key
authorization; however, its search complexity remains linear
in the number of outsourced documents \(N\) because each
candidate ciphertext must be individually tested.

In BVCRSA, the authenticated hierarchical range-cover index
is constructed once during data outsourcing, requiring
\(O(N\log N)\) time. For a query over \(d\) dimensions,
each queried interval is first decomposed into
\(m_c\) canonical nodes, where
\(m_c=O(\sum_{j=1}^{d}\log|D_j|)\).
Accordingly, trapdoor generation requires
\(O(m_c+k)\), where \(k\) denotes the number of user
attributes. During query processing, ABSE matching is
performed only for the canonical nodes, followed by
word-parallel bitmap intersections with complexity
\(O(\frac{N}{w}(|\mathcal U_Q|+d))\), where
\(|\mathcal U_Q|\) is the number of matched canonical nodes
and \(w\) is the machine-word size. The resulting
conjunctive bitmap identifies the matched record set
\(\mathcal R_Q\), over which homomorphic aggregation
requires \(O(|\mathcal R_Q|)\). Finally, verification
consists of Merkle-proof validation for the matched
canonical nodes, requiring \(O(|\mathcal U_Q|)\), together
with constant-time blockchain-state verification.

Consequently, the overall query complexity is dominated by
canonical-node decomposition, bitmap processing, and
aggregation over the matched records, rather than a linear
scan of all outsourced ciphertexts. This enables BVCRSA to
efficiently integrate logarithmic range decomposition,
bitmap-based conjunctive evaluation, encrypted aggregation,
and authenticated query verification within a unified
framework for large-scale outsourced IIoT analytics.

