constructs an attribute-dependent trapdoor whose size is
determined by the underlying LSSS access structure and
returns one encrypted response for each matched record.
The lattice-based scheme in Ref.~\cite{ref41} incurs the
largest communication overhead because both the trapdoor and
each returned ciphertext comprise multiple lattice vectors.
Although Ref.~\cite{ref44} employs a compact conjunctive
trapdoor and a constant-size aggregate signature, the cloud
must still transmit all matched ciphertexts, resulting in
response communication that grows linearly with the number
of matched records.

In BVCRSA, a query interval is first decomposed into
\(m_c\) canonical nodes. Accordingly, the request contains
one ABSE token and one bitmap selector for each canonical
node, yielding a request communication cost of
\(O(m_c)\). During query execution, bitmap intersections are
performed entirely at the cloud, and only the final
aggregation result is returned. Specifically, the response
consists of two aggregate ciphertexts, one conjunctive
bitmap, authenticated commitments, and Merkle proofs for the
matched canonical nodes, resulting in
\(O(|B_Q|+|\mathcal U_Q|\log n_e)\) communication in
addition to two constant-size aggregate ciphertexts.
Unlike existing schemes that return all matched encrypted
records, the response size of BVCRSA is independent of the
number of matched ciphertexts for aggregation queries.
Consequently, BVCRSA achieves communication-efficient
encrypted aggregation while preserving authenticated
query-state verification.



\subsection{Storage Overhead Analysis}

BVCRSA stores encrypted sensor records, authenticated
range-cover indexes, protected bitmaps, aggregation
ciphertexts, and blockchain commitments. Let $N$ denote the
number of outsourced records and $m_c$ the total number of
canonical interval nodes. The encrypted sensor records incur
$O(N)$ storage, while the authenticated range-cover index
requires $O(m_c)$ searchable-node ciphertexts and Merkle-tree
leaf commitments. Protected bitmaps require
$O(m_cN)$ bits because each canonical node maintains a
fixed-length bitmap over the indexed record space.
Aggregation metadata require one EC-ElGamal ciphertext per
record, yielding $O(N)$ additional storage. Finally, the
blockchain stores only compact epoch-level commitments
consisting of authenticated Merkle roots and signatures,
resulting in $O(E)$ on-chain storage for $E$ finalized
epochs. Consequently, the storage overhead is dominated by
the bitmap index, while blockchain storage remains
independent of the outsourced dataset size.
\subsection{Performance Evaluation}

We evaluate BVCRSA in terms of efficiency, scalability,
privacy-preserving aggregation, and authenticated
verification over large-scale outsourced IIoT data. The
evaluation considers four aspects: (i) searchable-index
construction, (ii) trapdoor generation and conjunctive range
query processing, (iii) encrypted aggregation, and (iv)
blockchain-based query-state verification.

BVCRSA is compared with representative searchable
encryption and range-query schemes, including
Scheme~\cite{ref38}, Trinity~\cite{ref39},
ABSE-Range~\cite{ref40}, Latt-IBEKS~\cite{ref41}, and
VC-KASE~\cite{ref44}. Since no existing scheme simultaneously supports
attribute-based searchable encryption, conjunctive range
queries, encrypted aggregation, authenticated
blockchain-backed verification, and threshold aggregate
decryption, only the functionalities shared by the
compared schemes (e.g., index construction, trapdoor
generation, query processing, and verification) are
evaluated comparatively. The encrypted aggregation
capability of BVCRSA, which is unsupported by the
baseline schemes, is evaluated separately through a
dedicated experiment. The threshold aggregate-decryption
cost is excluded from the comparative evaluation because
it is a post-processing operation not provided by the
baseline schemes.

\subsubsection*{\textbf{Experimental Setup}}

A BVCRSA prototype was implemented in Python~3.12.
The cryptographic components were simulated using
well-established cryptographic libraries to provide a
consistent evaluation environment. Attribute-based
searchable encryption was realized using BN128 bilinear
pairings via the \texttt{py\_ecc} library, while Threshold
EC-ElGamal homomorphic encryption was implemented over the
NIST P-256 elliptic curve. AES-GCM encryption was provided
by \texttt{PyCryptodome}, whereas SHA-256 and HMAC were
implemented using Python's native cryptographic libraries.
Ethereum smart contracts, developed in Solidity and
accessed through \texttt{Web3.py}, were used for
blockchain-anchored query-state verification. All baseline
schemes were reimplemented according to their original
algorithms and evaluated on the same hardware platform,
software environment, cryptographic libraries, and
comparable security settings whenever applicable to ensure
a fair comparison.

Experiments were conducted in a heterogeneous IIoT
environment consisting of a Raspberry Pi~4 Model~B (4~GB
RAM) for sensor-side operations, an Intel Core~i7 laptop
(16~GB RAM) for trapdoor generation, and an Intel Xeon
server (32~GB RAM, Ubuntu~22.04~LTS) for index
construction, query processing, aggregation, and
verification.

Synthetic IIoT records of the form
\(D=(m,k,t,v)\) were generated using 20 sensor categories,
with numerical values uniformly distributed over
\([0,100]\). The dataset size ranged from
\(10^3\) to \(2\times10^4\) records. Performance was
evaluated with respect to database size
(\(N=10^3\)--\(2\times10^4\)), query selectivity
(10\%--80\%), and the number of queried dimensions
(\(d=1\)--5). Measured metrics included index-construction
time, trapdoor-generation latency, query-processing time,
verification overhead, aggregation overhead, and storage
overhead. Unless otherwise specified, each reported result
represents the average of 20 independent runs under the
same configuration. Owing to the deterministic nature of
the evaluated cryptographic operations, the observed
variance was small; therefore, only average results are
reported for clarity.

\subsubsection{\textbf{Index Construction Time}}

This experiment evaluates the preprocessing overhead required to construct searchable indexes before outsourcing. The database size is varied from $1{,}000$ to $20{,}000$ records, while the number of searchable dimensions and access-policy size are fixed. Index-construction time includes encrypted node-tag generation, bitmap-commitment construction, aggregation-metadata initialization, and Merkle-root computation.

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.95\linewidth]{fig_index_construction.png}
\caption{Index-construction time versus database size.}
\label{fig:index_construction}
\end{figure}

Figure~\ref{fig:index_construction} compares the index-construction overhead of BVCRSA with Trinity~\cite{ref39}, ABSE-Range~\cite{ref40}, Latt-IBEKS~\cite{ref41}, and VC-KASE~\cite{ref44}. As the database size increases, all schemes incur higher preprocessing costs due to the growing number of searchable index entries. Among the evaluated schemes, VC-KASE achieves the lowest index-construction cost because it maintains a relatively lightweight keyword-based indexing structure. BVCRSA incurs slightly higher overhead owing to the construction of authenticated range-cover nodes, protected bitmap commitments, encrypted aggregation metadata, and Merkle-based verification structures. Nevertheless, these operations are performed only once during data outsourcing and therefore do not affect online query execution. Compared with Trinity and Latt-IBEKS, BVCRSA exhibits substantially lower preprocessing overhead because its index construction primarily relies on efficient hash computations, PRF evaluations, and incremental EC-ElGamal aggregation updates rather than expensive multidimensional encryption or lattice-based operations. 

\subsubsection{\textbf{Trapdoor Generation Time}}

This experiment evaluates the client-side overhead of trapdoor generation. The number of queried dimensions is varied from 1 to 5 while the database size is fixed at $N=10{,}000$ records. Trapdoor-generation time is measured as the elapsed time required to construct a valid search trapdoor before query submission.

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.95\linewidth]{fig_trapdoor_generation.png}
\caption{Trapdoor-generation time versus number of queried dimensions.}
\label{fig:trapdoor_generation}
\end{figure}

Figure~\ref{fig:trapdoor_generation} compares the trapdoor-generation overhead of BVCRSA with Trinity~\cite{ref39}, ABSE-Range~\cite{ref40}, Latt-IBEKS~\cite{ref41}, and VC-KASE~\cite{ref44}. As the number of queried dimensions increases, all schemes incur additional cost due to the need to encode more query predicates.

BVCRSA exhibits only a modest increase in latency, from approximately $0.9$~ms to $2.2$~ms when the number of queried dimensions increases from 1 to 5. This efficiency arises from canonical interval decomposition combined with lightweight hash, PRF, and attribute-bound token-generation operations. Since each dimension contributes only a logarithmic number of interval nodes, the trapdoor cost scales gradually with query complexity.

In contrast, Trinity~\cite{ref39}, ABSE-Range~\cite{ref40}, Latt-IBEKS~\cite{ref41}, and VC-KASE~\cite{ref44} incur higher overhead due to additional cryptographic operations during token construction. Overall, the results demonstrate that BVCRSA generates compact and efficient trapdoors while preserving query privacy and fine-grained access control, making it well suited for multidimensional encrypted range queries in large-scale IIoT environments.





\subsubsection{\textbf{Query Processing Time}}

Query-processing latency is a critical performance metric for outsourced searchable-encryption systems because it directly determines the responsiveness of encrypted data retrieval and analytics. This experiment evaluates the query-processing performance of BVCRSA under varying query selectivities, database sizes, and numbers of queried dimensions. The reported query-processing time includes encrypted search, bitmap filtering, and homomorphic aggregation, but excludes network communication and blockchain-access latency to isolate the efficiency of the search framework itself.


\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.95\linewidth]{fig_query_vs_range.png}
\caption{Query processing time versus range-query width.}
\label{fig:query_vs_range}
\end{figure}

Figure~\ref{fig:query_vs_range} evaluates the impact of range-query width on search performance. As the queried interval expands from $10\%$ to $80\%$ of the searchable domain, BVCRSA maintains consistently low query-processing latency, increasing only from approximately $0.04$~ms to $0.20$~ms. In contrast, VC-KASE~\cite{ref44} and Latt-IBEKS~\cite{ref41} require approximately $1$~ms, while ABSE-Range~\cite{ref40} and Trinity~\cite{ref39} incur substantially higher costs of approximately $40$~ms and $90$~ms, respectively. This result indicates that the hierarchical range-cover decomposition effectively limits the number of interval nodes processed during query evaluation, thereby reducing the impact of wider query ranges on search latency.

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.95\linewidth]{fig_query_vs_N.png}
\caption{Query processing time versus database size.}
\label{fig:query_vs_database}
\end{figure}

Figure~\ref{fig:query_vs_database} illustrates the scalability of query processing as the number of outsourced records increases from $1{,}000$ to $20{,}000$. BVCRSA consistently achieves the lowest query-processing latency, growing modestly from approximately $0.02$~ms to $0.45$~ms. In comparison, Trinity~\cite{ref39} and ABSE-Range~\cite{ref40} exhibit significantly higher latency, reaching approximately $180$~ms and $80$~ms, respectively, at the largest dataset size. Although Latt-IBEKS~\cite{ref41} and VC-KASE~\cite{ref44} perform better than Trinity and ABSE-Range, their query times still exceed $2$~ms. The superior scalability of BVCRSA stems from its authenticated range-cover index and conjunctive bitmap-filtering mechanism, which enable direct identification of candidate intervals without extensive ciphertext scanning.

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.95\linewidth]{fig_query_vs_d_conjunctive.png}
\caption{Query processing time versus number of queried dimensions.}
\label{fig:query_vs_dimension}
\end{figure}

Figure~\ref{fig:query_vs_dimension} examines the scalability of conjunctive multidimensional queries by varying the number of queried dimensions from 1 to 5. BVCRSA exhibits only a gradual increase in query-processing latency, from approximately $0.04$~ms to $0.25$~ms. Although Latt-IBEKS~\cite{ref41} and VC-KASE~\cite{ref44} maintain relatively stable performance across dimensions, their query-processing costs remain substantially higher at approximately $18$--$20$~ms and $3$~ms, respectively. This demonstrates that BVCRSA efficiently supports multidimensional range queries through dimension-level bitmap intersections, allowing conjunctive query evaluation with minimal additional overhead.

Overall, the results demonstrate that the combination of authenticated range-cover indexing and conjunctive bitmap filtering substantially reduces search overhead, enabling scalable and efficient multidimensional range-query processing for large-scale outsourced IIoT environments.

\subsubsection{\textbf{Query Throughput}}

This experiment evaluates the throughput of encrypted query processing to assess the efficiency of BVCRSA under increasing query workloads. The dataset size is fixed at $N=10{,}000$ records, while the number of submitted query requests varies from $100$ to $10{,}000$. Throughput is measured as

\[
\mathrm{Throughput}
=
\frac{Q_{\mathrm{completed}}}
     {T_{\mathrm{total}}},
\]

where $Q_{\mathrm{completed}}$ denotes the number of successfully processed queries and $T_{\mathrm{total}}$ denotes the total execution time.

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.95\linewidth]{fig_query_throughput_matched_colors.png}
\caption{Query throughput under increasing query workload.}
\label{fig:query_throughput}
\end{figure}

Figure~\ref{fig:query_throughput} compares the query throughput of BVCRSA with Trinity~\cite{ref39}, ABSE-Range~\cite{ref40}, Latt-IBEKS~\cite{ref41}, and VC-KASE~\cite{ref44}. BVCRSA consistently achieves the highest throughput across all workload sizes, significantly outperforming the baseline schemes. This improvement is attributed to the authenticated range-cover index and conjunctive bitmap-filtering mechanism, which enable efficient identification of matching records without extensive ciphertext scanning. In contrast, Trinity~\cite{ref39} and ABSE-Range~\cite{ref40} experience substantially lower throughput due to increasing index-traversal and cryptographic matching overhead as the workload grows. Latt-IBEKS~\cite{ref41} and VC-KASE~\cite{ref44} achieve higher throughput than Trinity and ABSE-Range but remain constrained by lattice-based computations and pairing-based ciphertext testing, respectively.

Overall, the results demonstrate that BVCRSA sustains high query throughput under increasing workloads while maintaining low query latency. The combination of authenticated indexing and compact trapdoor evaluation makes BVCRSA well suited for large-scale IIoT environments where multiple users and applications continuously issue encrypted range queries.

\subsubsection{\textbf{Verification Overhead}}

This experiment evaluates the cost of verifying search-query results. The number of returned results is varied from $50$ to $500$, while the database size and query parameters remain fixed. The comparison includes BVCRSA, Trinity~\cite{ref39}, and VC-KASE~\cite{ref44}, since these schemes provide explicit result-verification mechanisms. 
\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.95\linewidth]{fig_verification_overhead.png}
\caption{Verification time versus number of returned results.}
\label{fig:verification_overhead}
\end{figure}

Figure~\ref{fig:verification_overhead} compares the verification overhead of BVCRSA, Trinity~\cite{ref39}, and VC-KASE~\cite{ref44} under varying result-set sizes. BVCRSA consistently achieves the lowest verification latency, increasing only from approximately $0.25$~ms to $1.65$~ms as the number of returned results grows from $50$ to $500$. This behavior is consistent with the proposed verification design, where lightweight Merkle-proof validation scales with the number of matched results while blockchain-root verification incurs only a constant overhead. In contrast, Trinity~\cite{ref39} exhibits a substantially higher and nearly linear increase in verification cost because its verification process requires validating authentication information associated with each returned result. VC-KASE~\cite{ref44} maintains an almost constant verification latency since verification is dominated by a fixed number of pairing-based operations. However, its verification cost remains consistently higher than that of BVCRSA due to the computational expense of bilinear pairings.

\subsubsection{\textbf{Effect of Homomorphic Aggregation}}

This experiment evaluates the scalability benefit of the proposed bitmap-constrained homomorphic aggregation mechanism. The number of matched records is varied from 100 to 500 while the query configuration remains fixed. We compare the full BVCRSA framework against a Naive baseline that returns all matched encrypted records to the user without performing in-network aggregation.

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.95\linewidth]{fig_ablation_aggregation.png}
\caption{Effect of homomorphic aggregation versus naive record retrieval.}
\label{fig:ablation_aggregation}
\end{figure}

Figure~\ref{fig:ablation_aggregation} shows that the Naive approach incurs rapidly increasing latency as the number of matched records grows because all encrypted records must be transmitted and subsequently processed by the user. The execution time increases from approximately 180~ms to nearly 900~ms when the number of matched records reaches 500.

In contrast, BVCRSA performs aggregation directly over encrypted metadata maintained within the authenticated range-cover structure. Consequently, only compact aggregated ciphertexts and verification proofs are returned, substantially reducing communication and processing overhead. As a result, the execution time remains below 20~ms across all tested workloads and exhibits only a modest increase as the match volume grows.

These results demonstrate that the proposed homomorphic aggregation mechanism significantly improves query scalability while preserving data confidentiality and verifiability, making BVCRSA suitable for large-scale IIoT analytics workloads.

\subsubsection{\textbf{Aggregate-Recovery Scalability}}

This experiment evaluates the scalability of recovering
aggregate plaintexts using the Baby-Step Giant-Step (BSGS)
algorithm employed in the Threshold EC-ElGamal decryption
process. Since BSGS has
\(O(\sqrt{M_{\max}})\)
time complexity, where \(M_{\max}\) denotes the configured
maximum aggregate value, the recovery latency is expected to
increase sublinearly with the supported aggregation range.

The aggregate bound was varied from
\(10^{3}\) to \(10^{7}\), with each result averaged over
20 independent runs. As a baseline, we evaluated a
traditional EC-ElGamal implementation that recovers the
plaintext through naive linear search.

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{bsgs_scalability.png}
\caption{Aggregate-recovery latency versus maximum
supported aggregate value.}
\label{fig:bsgs}
\end{figure}

Fig.~\ref{fig:bsgs} shows that the recovery latency of
BVCRSA increases gradually with the configured aggregate
bound, following the expected
\(O(\sqrt{M_{\max}})\)
behavior. In contrast, the traditional linear-search
baseline grows approximately linearly with the plaintext
domain, resulting in substantially higher recovery latency
as the aggregation range increases.

For the evaluated IIoT workload, the maximum possible
aggregate sum is
\(2\times10^{6}\),
which remains well within the configured BSGS search space.
Therefore, aggregate recovery incurs only a small fraction
of the overall query-processing time, demonstrating that
lifted Threshold EC-ElGamal remains practical for
large-scale IIoT monitoring applications.

\section{Conclusion}

This paper presented \textbf{BVCRSA}, a blockchain-based
framework for verifiable conjunctive range search and
aggregation over encrypted IIoT data. BVCRSA integrates
attribute-based searchable encryption, authenticated
hierarchical range-cover indexing, protected bitmap
filtering, Threshold EC-ElGamal homomorphic aggregation, and
blockchain-anchored query-state verification into a unified
architecture. Unlike existing searchable encryption schemes
that primarily support secure retrieval, BVCRSA enables
fine-grained access control, conjunctive multi-range search,
privacy-preserving aggregation, threshold aggregate
decryption, and verifiable query processing within a single
framework. Experimental results
demonstrated efficient trapdoor generation, practical
bitmap-based query processing, low verification overhead,
and scalable index construction while providing integrated
aggregation and verifiable analytics beyond the capabilities
of representative searchable range-query schemes. Future work will investigate efficient user and attribute revocation, dynamic index updates, large-scale evaluation using real-world IIoT datasets, end-to-end performance analysis incorporating network communication and blockchain latency, distributed or partially trusted key management, edge-assisted query processing, and post-quantum cryptographic primitives to further enhance the scalability, deployment practicality, and long-term security of BVCRSA.


